			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Smart Phones
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1793652">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							This is precisely why the on-call phone at my workplace is a Blackberry.<br />
<br />
The battery lasts more than a week even if you're taking multiple calls a night for a few minutes at a time.<br />
<br />
Despite hating blackberries, one of our lead techs insisted we use one for this purpose because so many of our techs on the on-call rotation would forget to return the charger with the phone at the end of their week.<br />
<br />
Sure, all it does is take automatically generated calls and mails from the 24 hour monitoring system, but it still has at LEAST 3 to 4 times the battery life of a carefully configured modern smartphone. (carefully configured as in all wireless, gps, apps, features, etc turned OFF to reach maximum battery life).<br />
<br />
With GPS and Bluetooth turned off on my Droid4, even with a live wallpaper and the thing set to push mode for e-mail, I get 24-48 hours of &quot;idle&quot;<font size="1"><sup>*1</sup></font> battery life (the latter when I'm regularly connected via wireless because verizon roaming sucks battery like nobody's business and I can't turn off G4 and go solely with the much more present G3 coverage, so it constantly switches back and forth) and about 8 hours of heavy use<sup><font size="1">*2</font></sup> life.<br />
<br />
<br />
<font size="1"><sup>*1</sup></font>Mail still checked by push, so while &quot;idle&quot; the screen is off mail still comes through via exchange activesync constantly.<br />
<br />
<font size="1"><sup>*2</sup></font>More than three apps running in the background, some GPS, multiple phone calls, heavy browsing, occasional youtube or pandora.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
